In [ ]:
def visualize_input(i, y):
    img = X_train[i].reshape(28,28)
    plt.imshow(img, cmap='gray')
    plt.title(f"Label : {y[i]}")
    width, height = img.shape
    thresh = img.max()/2.5
    for x in range(width):
        for y in range(height):
            plt.annotate(str(img[x][y]), xy=(y,x),
                        horizontalalignment='center',
                        verticalalignment='center',
                        color='white' if img[x][y]<thresh else 'black')
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
In [ ]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (15,11)) 
visualize_input(1, y_train)

The plot given above shows pixel values with colors. With these pixel values, we can see the shades in the image. Here 255 shows pure white color whereas less than 255 shows different shades of grey. 0 pixel value means pure black color whith is the background color in this case.

3. Define and train neural network:¶

Split the data:

In [ ]:
X_train, X_validate, y_train, y_validate = train_test_split(X_train, y_train, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)


print("Training: ",X_train.shape[0]) 
print("Validate: ",X_validate.shape[0])
print("Test:", X_test.shape[0])

Training:  48000
Validate:  12000
Test: 10000

Define model:¶

In [ ]:
model = keras.Sequential([
    layers.Dense(512, activation="relu"),
    layers.Dense(10, activation="softmax")
])

Sequential: Defines a sequence of layers in the neural network.
Dense: Adds a layer of neurons
Each layer of neurons need an activation function to tell them what to do. There are a lot of options, but just use these for now:

ReLU means:
if x > 0:
return x

else:
return 0

Compile model:

In [ ]:
model.compile(optimizer="rmsprop",  
              loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
              metrics=["accuracy"])

Optimizer - This is how the model is updated based on the data it sees and its loss function.
Loss function - This calculates how accurate the model is during training.
Metrics - Used to monitor the training and testing steps.

Train model:¶

In [ ]:
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=5, batch_size=128, validation_data=(X_validate,y_validate))

6. High Precision for class 5:¶

We saw earlier that for test data:
Precision: 0.98
Recall: 0.92

To increase the precision without changing or retraining model, we studied that we need to increase threshold.

In [ ]:
y_scores = y_test_pred[:, 5]
y5 = (y_test == 5)

threshold = 0.6 
y_pred_high_precision = (y_scores > threshold)

precision = precision_score(y5, y_pred_high_precision)
recall = recall_score(y5, y_pred_high_precision)

print(f"When threshold increased to: {threshold}\nPrecision: {precision:.4f}\nRecall: {recall:.4f}")

When threshold increased to: 0.6
Precision: 0.9901
Recall: 0.9040

By doing this the precision value increased from 0.98 to 0.99.
Precision increases because the values with high confidence of being positive will be classified and recall i.e the ratio (tp/tp+np) decreases.

7. High Recall for Class 5:¶

To increase the recall value, decrease threshold

In [ ]:
y_scores = y_test_pred[:, 5]
y5 = (y_test == 5)

threshold = 0.3
y_pred_high_recall = (y_scores > threshold)

precision = precision_score(y5, y_pred_high_recall)
recall = recall_score(y5, y_pred_high_recall)

print(f"When threshold decreased to: {threshold}\nPrecision: {precision:.4f}\nRecall: {recall:.4f}")

When threshold decreased to: 0.3
Precision: 0.9790
Recall: 0.9340

Recall increased from 0.92 to 0.93
When the threshold value is decreased, recall increases whereas precision decreases.
It is because all those which had low predicted probability of will also be classified as positive.
